  "prompt": "What are some examples of an ionic bond?",
  "response": "Ionic bonds are chemical bonds formed between two ions with opposite charges, typically between a metal and a non-metal. Here are some common examples of compounds with ionic bonds:\n\n1. **Sodium Chloride (NaCl)**: Commonly known as table salt, this compound is formed by the transfer of an electron from a sodium atom to a chlorine atom, resulting in a positively charged sodium ion (Na\u207a) and a negatively charged chloride ion (Cl\u207b).\n\n2. **Potassium Bromide (KBr)**: This compound is formed when a potassium atom donates an electron to a bromine atom. The result is a potassium ion (K\u207a) and a bromide ion (Br\u207b).\n\n3. **Magnesium Oxide (MgO)**: Magnesium transfers two electrons to an oxygen atom. This transfer creates a positively charged magnesium ion (Mg\u00b2\u207a) and a negatively charged oxide ion (O\u00b2\u207b).\n\n4. **Calcium Chloride (CaCl\u2082)**: Calcium donates two electrons, one to each of two chlorine atoms, forming a calcium ion (Ca\u00b2\u207a) and two chloride ions (Cl\u207b).\n\n5. **Aluminum Oxide (Al\u2082O\u2083)**: In this compound, aluminum ions (Al\u00b3\u207a) and oxide ions (O\u00b2\u207b) bond together. Aluminum loses three electrons and oxygen gains two electrons to form this compound.\n\nThese compounds exhibit strong electrostatic forces of attraction between the oppositely charged ions, leading to relatively high melting and boiling points, and they often dissolve in water to form electrolytic solutions.",
